Boil a large #pot{} of salted @water{to taste} for the @egg noodles{150%g}.

When the water is boiling, add the noodles and cook until softened, ~{4-6%mins}.

Drain in a #sieve{} then return to the pot, off the heat.

Add a splash of @oil{to taste} and toss to prevent sticking.

> TIP: If you're in a hurry you can boil the water in your kettle.

Meanwhile, roughly chop the @mushrooms{250%g}(roughly chopped).

Thinly slice the @chives{5%g}(thinly sliced) (use scissors if you prefer).

Stir the @coconut milk{1%pack} (or shake the packet) to dissolve any lumps.

Place a large pan over high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Once the pan is very hot, sear the @Irish beef strips{250%g} until cooked
through, shifting as they colour, ~{2-3%mins}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw meat and its packaging.
> Meat is safe to eat when the outside is browned.

Remove from the pan and cover to keep warm.

Return the pan to high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

When hot, add the mushrooms to the pan. Season with @salt{to taste} and
@pepper{to taste}.

Fry until browned, stirring occasionally, ~{5-6%mins}.

Add the @Thai style spice mix{2%sachets} and @red Thai style paste{2%sachets}
to the pan and cook until fragrant, ~{1%min}.

Add the coconut milk, @water{75%ml} and half the chives.

Cover and simmer for ~{5-7%mins}.

Add a splash of water to loosen the sauce if required. Season to taste with
salt and pepper.

Toss the drained noodles and beef strips in the sauce to warm through and coat
well.

Divide the beef and mushroom noodles between bowls.

Top with a sprinkling of the remaining chives.